Problem

We aim to use campaign financing data - specifically, direct contribution amounts from Political Action Committees (PACs) to candidates - to forecast election outcomes for congressional candidates. A PAC is an organization that pools campaign contributions from members and donates those funds to campaigns for or against candidates, ballot initiatives, or legislation.

Data Source

We obtained our data from the Center for Responsive Politics, which is a non-profit, non-partisan research group based in Washington, D.C. It tracks the effects of money and lobbying on elections and public policy, and maintains a public online database of its information at www.opensecrets.org.

The campaign finance data for every election cycle includes five tables: individual contributions, candidates, FEC committees, PAC to canddiates, and PAC to PACs. For the purposes of our study, we focused mainly on the candidates and PAC to candidates tables. We used data from the past three cycles: 2018, 2016, and 2014. We also used reference data (CRP categories) to obtain the PAC industry codes. Finally, the Open Data Users Guide provided data dictionaries for all the tables.

Out data can be downloaded here: https://drive.google.com/open?id=1HkTuv2nSX-kCCItt2aHsGwqwcoiKHrlr

read.multisep <- function(File,sep) {
    Lines <- readLines(File)
    Matrix <- do.call(rbind,strsplit(Lines, sep, fixed = TRUE))
    DataFrame <- structure(data.frame(Matrix))
    DataFrame[] <- lapply(DataFrame, type.convert)
    DataFrame
}
cands <- read.multisep("cands18.txt",sep="|,|")

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

We then performed some EDA to better understand our dataset. In order to clean the data, we used the RecipCode column, which comprises of two characters that indicate the Party and Status of candidates. The abbreviations are as follows:
- Party: D for Democratic, R for Republican, I for Independent, L for Libertarian, 3 for third party, U for unknown
- Status: W for Winner, L for Loser, I for Incumbent, C for Challenger, O for Open Seat, N for Non-Incumbent
Note: N is reserved for candidates that are neither in office nor running during the cycle in question.

We used Rs dplyr package to clean the data prior to visualization. This included operations such as filtering out missing or mislabeled data, removing rows with RecipCodes ending with I, C, O, or N, and removing rows with NA values in contribution amount when calculating the total or average contribution.

Data Preprocessing

We performed data preprocessing on the two data tables we used: Candidates and PAC to Candidates. We first regrouped the PACs contributions files (of 2014,2016 and 2018), merging them with the industries table.It stores the codes corresponding to the industries types of the different PACs. From the PAC tables of 2018, 2016, and 2014, we selected direct contributions, grouped them by candidate ID, PAC industry or timeframe before 2018 elections (i.e.3 months, 6 months, or 12 months), summed total contributions to each candidate for the years 2014 and 2016, summed total contributions per industry to each candidate for the year 2018.

We then performed a left join of the 2018 candidate table to the PAC contribution data from the three cycles. We further cleaned the data by mutating a new column Outcome to indicate the Winner (1) or Loser (0) in the election. We only kept contributions made before Election Day (i.e.November 6th, 2018), and we replaced all NA contributions with 0. We kept only distinct candidate IDs and removed duplicate rows. Finally, we also added the number of candidates per district as an indicator of the competitiveness of the race.

Model Training & Validation

df <- read.csv("data.csv",header=T)

The following variables are present in the dataframe that we used to construct our models:
- Party: The party of the candidate. [Categorical: D, R, I, L, 3, U]
- CurrCand: Indicates whether the candidate is currently running for federal office. If a candidate loses a primary or drops out of the race, this field becomes blank. [Binary]
- CycleCand: Indicates whether the candidate ever ran for federal office during the cycle in question. Any candidate who filed to run for office or otherwise formally declared intention to run. This does NOT change if the candidate drops out or loses a primary. [Binary]
- CRPICO: Identifies the type of candidate. [Categorical: I, C, O]
- NoPacs: Identifies whether candidate has publicly committed to forego contributions from PACs. [Binary]
- Amount_2014: Total amount of contributions from PACs toward each candidate for the 2014 cycle. [Numeric]
- Amount_2016: Total amount of contributions from PACs toward each candidate for the 2016 cycle. [Numeric]
- Amount_2018: Total amount of contributions from PACs toward each candidate for the 2018 cycle. [Numeric]
- Amount_Sector_2018: Total amount of contributions from PACs of a given sector toward each candidate for 2018 cycle. [Numeric]
- Three_M_Cont_2018: Total amount of contributions from PACs toward each candidate for 2018 cycle, during the three months preceding the election. [Numeric]
- Six_M_Cont_2018: Total amount of contributions from PACs toward each candidate for 2018 cycle, during the six months preceding the election. [Numeric]
- Twelve_M_Cont_2018: Total amount of contributions from PACs toward each candidate for 2018 cycle, during the 12 months preceding the election. [Numeric]
- N_candidates_final: Number of candidates on the ballot on the election day of the 2018 cycle. [Numeric]

First, we decided to perform a penalized logistic regression through LASSO (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator). We did a stratified split of the candidates into training (70%) and testing (30%) set based on the outcome variable.

We used cv.glmnet for cross-validation to select best lambda. In particular, we did a 10-fold cross validation, selected for the best Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), and picked lambda.min, which gives the minimum mean cross-validated error. We then obtained estimates of each coefficient, determined the in-sample threshold, accuracy, prediction and recall, and used this threshold to generate our out-of-sample prediction and test results.

set.seed(123)
df_split <- sample.split(df$Outcome,SplitRatio=0.7)
train <- df[df_split==T,]
test <- df[df_split==F,]

Model 1

For our first model, we used the party, status, and amount of PAC contributions received by the candidate from 2014, 2016, and 2018 as the independent variables. Model 1 has an out-of-sample AUC of 0.9768.

set.seed(123)

X_train <- sparse.model.matrix(~0+factor(Party)+Amount_2014+Amount_2016+Amount_2018+factor(CRPICO)
                               ,data=train)
y_train <- train$Outcome

X_test <- sparse.model.matrix(~0+factor(Party)+Amount_2014+Amount_2016+Amount_2018+factor(CRPICO)
                              ,data=test)
y_test <- test$Outcome

cv_lasso <- cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train, family = "binomial",
                      alpha = 1, nfolds = 10, type.measure = "auc")

model <- glmnet(X_train,y_train,alpha=1,family="binomial",lambda=cv_lasso$lambda.min)

coefs <- data.frame(variable=rownames(coef(model)),estimate=(coef(model)[,1]))
rownames(coefs) <- 1:nrow(coefs)

Results & Extensions

On a surface level, we found that PAC contribution can be a good indicator of electoral success. For instance, according to Model 3, a contribution increase of $45000 from Defense PAC contributions doubles the odds of winning. However, we have also found that incumbents have a very high probability of reelection. Even more, as evidenced by Model 2, this variable is almost enough to predict the probability of election of a candidate. Obviously, there are several factors at work behind the incumbency advantage. Also, incumbents also tend to get more contributions from PACs. The causal relationship here is unclear - we do not know whether the best candidates raise more money, or if raising more money contributed to their electoral victory.

In particular, the strong apparent relationship between incumbency and amount raised led us to:

-: predict incumbency from the PACs contributions (and confirm the hints given by our models and the EDA) -: use causal inference (matching) to determine the effect of incumbency over election results, independently (as much as possible) of contributions.

Predicting Incumbency from contributions

We first endeavoured to predict the CRPICO variable (Challenger, Incumbent, Open Seat) from the amount of contributions (per industry and timeframe).

Instead of logistic regression, we decided to use classification trees. They have several advantages:

  • they mimick human decision-making
  • they select the most relevant variables for us
  • they can deliver nonlinear predictions that are hard to capture with logistic regression

We trained our tree on a training dataset, and determined both in-sample/out-of sample accuracy and confusion matrixes.

set.seed(02138)
df_split <- sample.split(df$CRPICO,SplitRatio=0.7)
train <- df[df_split==T,]
test <- df[df_split==F,]


formula_status_money <- as.formula(paste("CRPICO~",formula,collapse=""))
tree1 <- rpart(formula_status_money,
data = train , method="class",
minbucket=5, cp=0.004)

prp(tree1,digits = 3,varlen=0,faclen=0)

To interpret the trees, we take a given candidate for which we know the different amounts of contributions. Given these different values, we follow the splits made by the tree until the final node, which outputs the type of the candidate. For each split, we go to the left when the candidate verifies the assertion at the split, and right in the other case.

The first variables are often the most important. Here, a high amount (more than $35 700) of money raised in 2016 immediately gives out that the candidate is an incumbent in 2018. Also, if a candidate did not raise this amount in 2016 but has received significant contributions from two industries (Finance/Insurance/Real Estate and Electronics), our model predicts him to be an incumbent.

pred_train <- predict(tree1,newdata= train,type="class")

confusion <- table(train$CRPICO, pred_train)
confusion
##    pred_train
##        C    I    O
##   C 1057   14   24
##   I    2  281    6
##   O  399    8  137
accuracy <- (confusion[1,1]+confusion[2,2]+confusion[3,3])/sum(confusion)
print("Accuracy on train")
## [1] "Accuracy on train"
print(accuracy)
## [1] 0.7650415
print("Percentage of Open seats candidates predicted as Challenger")
## [1] "Percentage of Open seats candidates predicted as Challenger"
print(confusion[3,1]/sum(confusion[3,])    )
## [1] 0.7334559
pred_test <- predict(tree1,newdata= test,type="class")

confusion <- table(test$CRPICO, pred_test)
confusion
##    pred_test
##       C   I   O
##   C 438   6  25
##   I   3 119   2
##   O 202   2  29

print("Accuracy on test")
## [1] "Accuracy on test"
print(accuracy)
## [1] 0.7094431
print("Percentage of Open seats candidates predicted as Challenger")
## [1] "Percentage of Open seats candidates predicted as Challenger"
print(confusion[3,1]/sum(confusion[3,])    )
## [1] 0.8669528

On both sets, the accuracy is not bad (0.76 on train and 0.71 on test). Challengers and Incumbents candidates are almost all well predicted. However, most of the open seats candidates are predicted to be challengers. Our model seems to have trouble differentiating them. As a sidenote, more complex splits in the tree (those deeper) were indeed splits between C and O.

Matching: Effect of Incumbency on Election Results

One major issue we have had in predicting election results lies in the fact that many of the covariates are highly correlated. In particular, incumbents tend to receive more contributions, and similar industries contribute to the same types of candidates. In order to alleviate this kind of problem, we tried to use a causal inference technique called matching.

We removed the open seats districts and divided the candidates between incumbents (I) and non incumbents. The idea is to pair each incumbent with a similar (in terms of covariates) non incumbent. We end up with two groups of candidates as close as possible, which only differ by the treatment(incumbency). If our matching is good and the groups are similar enough, we would be able to directly measure the effect of incumbency over election outcomes.

The covariates we used are all the features corresponding to contributions:

num_variables
##  [1] "Amount_2014"                              
##  [2] "Amount_2016"                              
##  [3] "Three_M_Cont_2018"                        
##  [4] "Six_M_Cont_2018"                          
##  [5] "Twelve_M_Cont_2018"                       
##  [6] "Amount_Agribusiness_2018"                 
##  [7] "Amount_Candidate_2018"                    
##  [8] "Amount_Communications_Electronics_2018"   
##  [9] "Amount_Construction_2018"                 
## [10] "Amount_Defense_2018"                      
## [11] "Amount_Energy_Natural_Resources_2018"     
## [12] "Amount_Finance_Insurance_Real_Estate_2018"
## [13] "Amount_Health_2018"                       
## [14] "Amount_Ideological_Single_Issue_2018"     
## [15] "Amount_Joint_Candidate_Cmtes_2018"        
## [16] "Amount_Labor_2018"                        
## [17] "Amount_Lawyers_Lobbyists_2018"            
## [18] "Amount_Misc_Business_2018"                
## [19] "Amount_Non_contribution_2018"             
## [20] "Amount_Other_2018"                        
## [21] "Amount_Party_Cmtes_2018"                  
## [22] "Amount_Transportation_2018"               
## [23] "Amount_Unknown_2018"

The variable used to measure the similarity is the absolute standardized mean difference. It is defined for each covariate. If \(A\) is an amount,

\[ SMD(A)= \frac{|Mean_{I}(A) -Mean_{Non-I}(A)|}{Standard~deviation~of~A~between~the~two~groups} \]

We then plot the SMD for each covariate, between the groups of incumbents and non-incumbents.

df_matching <- df %>% filter(CRPICO !='O')
df_matching$incumb<- df_matching$CRPICO=="I"
bl_c_i <- bal.tab(df_matching[num_variables], treat = df_matching$incumb, estimand="ATT", continuous="std")
love.plot(x = bl_c_i, stat = "mean.diffs", abs = TRUE, var.order = "unadjusted", threshold = 0.1)

As we can notice, the SMD is high for most of the covariates. The dashed line (for SMD=0.1) corresponds to the usual threshold above which the two groups are considered too dissimilar. Only 3 variables have a SMD close to 0.1, and most are close to 1.5.

We then matched the elements of the two groups. As we have less incumbents (413) than non-incumbents (1564), we are going to select only 414 non incumbents.

match_c_i <- Match(Tr=df_matching$incumb, M=1, X=df_matching[num_variables])

matched_c_i<- df_matching[unlist(match_c_i[c("index.treated","index.control")]), ]


#m_tab_c_i <- CreateTableOne(vars=num_variables, strat="incumb", data=matched_c_i, test=FALSE)
#print(m_tab_c_i,smd=TRUE)

matched_c_i$incumb<- as.numeric(matched_c_i$incumb)

balance_c_i <- bal.tab(matched_c_i[num_variables], treat = matched_c_i$incumb, estimand="ATT", continuous="std")
love.plot(x = balance_c_i, stat = "mean.diffs", abs = TRUE, var.order = "unadjusted", threshold = 0.1)

After matching, most of the covariates have lower SMD. In particular, the maximum SMD is now 1, with 2/3 of the variables having 0.5 or less SMD. The matching has been useful to reduce the differences among the two groups. However, for causal inference purpose, they are still quite dissimilar and we need to exercise caution with our results.

We finally compute the average treatment effect (ATE) of incumbency.

mean(df_matching$Outcome[df_matching$incumb==TRUE])-mean(df_matching$Outcome[df_matching$incumb==FALSE])
## [1] 0.882048

This ATE is very high and seems to indicate that incumbency in itself is extremely valuable for re election.

Our future steps involve examining more data from previous election cycles. Since congressional elections take place every 2 years, and all 435 Representatives serve 2-year terms, data is more frequent and comprehensive. On the other hand, only 35 seats in the Senate were up for election in 2018, and Senators serve 6-year terms, so our model was unable to capture all Senators. We can also use more efficient causal inference techniques to understand the role of incumbency and monetary contributions.
